Chapter 9: The Investigation
The sterilized white lights of the Academy’s infirmary were a different kind of blinding. There were no monsters here, just the rhythmic beep-beep of Essence-monitors and the smell of antiseptic.
Ren sat on the edge of a high-tech cot. A silver-rimmed drone hovered three inches from his face, its red laser-eye scanning his retinas.
"Patient #4092. Ren. Affinity: 0.00%," the drone’s synthesized voice droned. "No internal Essence burns detected. No Void-contamination in the bloodstream. Conclusion: Physical trauma only. High levels of fatigue."
The door slid open with a sharp hiss. Warden Vane stepped in, his suit as crisp as if he hadn't just spent the night coordinating a mass recovery of traumatized students. Behind him stood two Association Enforcers, their faces hidden behind matte-black visors.
"You’re a lucky young man, Ren," Vane said, his smile not reaching his eyes. He pulled up a holographic chair and sat. "To survive a Grade 3 Breach without a single point of Essence to defend yourself... it’s a miracle. Or a very interesting anomaly."
Ren stared at the floor. He could feel the 'Cache' in the back of his mind—a heavy, cold pressure. "I got lucky. Kaelen and Mira did the fighting. I just hid in the rubble."
[Warning: Heart rate elevated. Deception Protocol active.]
"Is that so?" Vane leaned in. "Because Kaelen’s testimony says he was incapacitated. Mira says she couldn't see through the fog. And Jax... well, Jax is currently in a psychiatric ward claiming that a 'Zero' deleted a monster with his bare hands."
"Jax was injured," Ren said, finally meeting Vane’s gaze. "He was hallucinating from the Void-rot."
Vane tapped his fingers on his knee. "The console at Site 9 was melted from the inside out, Ren. Molecular decay. The same kind of decay found on a fire hydrant nearby. The Association’s engineers are baffled. They say it looks like the 'Logic' of the metal was simply... erased."
"I wouldn't know anything about that, Warden. I’m a student. I study the textbooks you give us."
Vane stood up slowly. The air in the room grew heavy. A faint purple shimmer flickered around his cufflinks. "The textbooks are for the students who follow the rules, Ren. But the Association has a special place for those who... break the curve."
The door opened again, interrupting the tension. Professor Aris—or rather, the real Professor Aris—walked in. She was leaning on a cane, her arm in a sling. She looked tired, but her eyes were sharp.
"Warden," she said, her voice cool. "The Ethics Committee is waiting for your report on the 'interference' at Site 9. You shouldn't be bothering a recovering student."
Vane looked at Aris, then back at Ren. He smoothed his tie. "Of course. We’re all on the same team here, aren't we? Keeping the world safe."
He signaled to the Enforcers and walked out. Aris waited until the door fully sealed. She didn't sit down. She walked to the window, looking out at the Academy grounds where a new, massive "security" pylon was being erected.
"He doesn't believe you," Aris said, her back to him.
"I know," Ren replied.
"Neither do I." She turned around. "I was in the command tent when the signal died. I saw the data-stream flicker. For three seconds, the entire global network for the Association went dark. And when it came back, three terabytes of student data were missing from the central server."
Ren felt the silver mark on his hand pulse.
"The thing at the site," Ren whispered. "The one that looked like you. It called the Association 'antivirus software'."
Aris went deathly still. She walked over and gripped the rail of Ren’s bed. "If you know that... if you saw the 'Hand', then you’re in more danger than a Void-larva in a furnace. The Association isn't just investigating the breach, Ren. They’re looking for the 'Cache'."
